{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644770"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:07:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:07:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18063"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18063"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.72,0,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10777"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75045"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10777"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18063"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60552"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5759"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25131"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26126"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75045","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75045"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EConscientious objection refers to the right of healthcare providers to refuse participation in certain legal medical procedures based on moral or religious grounds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the professional obligations of healthcare providers when exercising conscientious objection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Must document objections in medical records","Must refer patients to willing practitioners","Should explain religious beliefs to patients","May transfer care without patient consent","Can decline all related future care"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct professional obligation when exercising conscientious objection is that providers \u003Cstrong\u003Emust refer patients to willing practitioners\u003C/strong\u003E. This ensures patients maintain access to legal medical care while respecting the provider\u0027s moral beliefs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMust document objections in medical records\u003C/strong\u003E - While documentation is good practice, this is not a specific requirement for conscientious objection, as the primary focus should be on ensuring continued patient care.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShould explain religious beliefs to patients\u003C/strong\u003E - Healthcare providers do not need to disclose or justify their personal beliefs, as this may inappropriately influence or distress patients.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMay transfer care without patient consent\u003C/strong\u003E - Patient consent and involvement are essential in the referral process, as transferring care without consent breaches patient autonomy.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECan decline all related future care\u003C/strong\u003E - Healthcare providers must assess each situation individually and cannot make blanket refusals, particularly for emergency situations.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle is balancing respect for healthcare providers\u0027 moral beliefs with the ethical obligation to ensure patients can access legal medical care. This is achieved through appropriate referral to willing practitioners.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Conscientious objection allows healthcare providers to refuse to participate in legal medical procedures that conflict with their personal moral or religious beliefs.","Healthcare providers must refer patients to willing practitioners when exercising conscientious objection.","Conscientious objection cannot be exercised in medical emergencies where delay would risk patient harm."],"references":["Conscientious objection - 2019. Australian Medical Association. 2019. Available from: https://www.ama.com.au/position-statement/conscientious-objection-2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60552"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18063"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60552"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T20:59:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T21:00:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10777"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75045"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null